UPDATE [dbo].[people]
    SET biography = N'James McDougall is a Canadian actor and filmmaker. He was raised in the small town of Cobourg Ontario, the son of Gail McDougall, a prison manager, and John McDougall, an English teacher. Throughout elementary and high school, acting and filmmaking were always a passion for James. Whether it was performing in local plays, school theater, or filming his own home movies with friends.

This led him to major in drama at Canterbury Arts High School and he went on to York University to study theater for one year. James then moved back to Ottawa to begin performing on stage in musicals and dramatic productions with ASNY, Orleans Young Players, and GOYA. He ventured to Victoria B.C. and acted in shows with Atomic Vaudeville, Theatre Inconnu, and Langham Court Theater.

After a few years in British Columbia James traveled back to his home province of Ontario and embraced the film and television scene in Toronto. He immersed himself in the world of on-camera acting and filmmaking. By creating his own projects, training and constantly honing his craft, and working at Armstrong Acting Studios where he filmed thousands of hours of classes as well as casting sessions with some the top casting directors in Canada, James got to know the industry from the inside out as he quickly built up his on-screen resume.

A few breakout roles include getting cast as the lead actor in Vincenzo Natalinulls segment in the anthology horror film ABCs of Death 2 (2014), playing Santa Claus in Michael Dowsenulls heartwarming HBO Max film 8-Bit Christmas (2021) and landing a supporting role as the bumbling criminal Hammond in Jonathan Milott and Cary Murnionulls hit thriller Becky (2020) where he acted alongside Kevin James, Lulu Wilson, and Joel McHale.

James has also spent over a decade working behind the scenes writing, directing, and producing content at Mountain Man Media. Walking Supply (2016), a short film he co-wrote with Derek Barnes, went on to debut at The Toronto International Short Film Festival. The concept was soon developed into the feature film Whiteout (2023), which James not only co-wrote but starred in as the role of Henry. The harrowing survival thriller was filmed in the dead of winter, sold at the Cannes Film Market, and landed distribution with Saban Films and Myriad Pictures.

In 2021, James founded his own production company called Galebreak Studios, which focuses on telling captivating narrative stories of all genres, both short and feature length.', dob = '1986-03-30', photo_url = 'https://image.tmdb.org/t/p/w500/ounyHPElQ6jYcCGITmTdVJuiz5n.jpg'
    WHERE id = 673;
UPDATE [dbo].[people]
    SET biography = N'Lea Myren (born April 21, 2001) is a Norwegian actress and fashion model. She gained recognition for her role as Maya in NRKnulls drama series Jenter (2013–2015; 2018). Later, she played Jeanette in NRKnulls sitcom Itnulls All Relatives (from 2020) and Monica Larsen in TV 2nulls drama series Kids in Crime (from 2022). In 2025, she portrayed Elvira in The Ugly Stepsister, which premiered at the Sundance Film Festival.

She was born in Elverum, Norway, and grew up in Hamar and Oslo. Myren studied drama at Hartvig Nissen School, graduating in 2020, and later pursued physical theater at LnullÉcole Internationale de Théâtre Jacques Lecoq in Paris.

Her career began in 2009, when she debuted in NRK’s children’s series Superia. Since then, she has appeared in several Norwegian TV series, including Side om side (2018) and Blank (2019). In addition to acting, she has worked as a fashion model, collaborating with brands like Also Worldwide.', dob = '2001-04-21', photo_url = 'https://image.tmdb.org/t/p/w500/wRsFFN1lhGcVM5kQFnLRW0wlQXR.jpg'
