UPDATE [dbo].[people]
    SET biography = N'Ryan Meinerding is an American concept artist and the Head of Visual Development at Marvel Studios, a role in which he has been instrumental since the early days of the Marvel Cinematic Universe (MCU). He is also a member of the Marvel Studios Parliament. Growing up in suburban Northeast Ohio, Meinerding developed a passion for art at a young age, initially wielding crayons and later transitioning to an airbrush during high school. He pursued a degree in Industrial Design at the University of Notre Dame. Furthermore, he refined his skills in Illustration at the Art Centre College of Design. After completing his education, he collaborated with renowned concept artist Iain McCaig on a project that led to a meeting with director Jon Favreau. Favreau, impressed by Meinerdingnulls work, hired him as an illustrator for the 2008 film Iron Man, marking the beginning of his long-standing association with Marvel Studios.

He served as an illustrator for Iron Man, a conceptual illustrator for Iron Man 2, and a visual development supervisor for Thor and Captain America: The First Avenger. His role expanded as the MCU grew, and he became the co-head of visual development. Subsequently, he took on the position of Head of Visual Development, overseeing the design of characters and costumes for numerous films, including Iron Man 3, Captain America: The Winter Soldier, Avengers: Age of Ultron, Doctor Strange, Black Panther, Avengers: Infinity War, Avengers: Endgame, and Spider-Man: No Way Home. His work also extended to television series such as Daredevil, The Falcon and The Winter Soldier, Loki, and What If...?, where he developed the animation style inspired by classic American illustrators like J.C. Leyendecker and Norman Rockwell.

Beyond his design work, Meinerding has shared his expertise through publications and interviews. He authored The Art of Iron Man 3 and co-wrote How to Paint Characters the Marvel Studios Way. His insights into the creative process have been featured in the documentary series Assembled, specifically in episodes like The Making of What If...? and The Making of Black Panther: Wakanda Forever. In 2024, his contributions were further celebrated with the release of Marvel Studios: The Art of Ryan Meinerding. This comprehensive book showcases over 500 illustrations and provides an in-depth look at his creative journey and the evolution of the MCUnulls visual identity.', dob = null, photo_url = 'https://image.tmdb.org/t/p/w500/cDfao2DmBHqvjysYZxuO5q6U0Pm.jpg'
    WHERE id = 2886;
UPDATE [dbo].[people]
    SET biography = N'Robert Allman is a visual effects supervisor at Framestore, based in London. He earned an MA in Computer Animation from London Guildhall in 1997. He began his career immediately afterwards by joining Mill Film. In those early years, he contributed to blockbuster films such as Gladiator (2000), Lara Croft: Tomb Raider (2001) and the early entries in the Harry Potter franchise.

After gaining experience in technical and CG roles, he joined Framestore as a Technical Director. There, he re-entered the Harry Potter world, working on Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban (2004) and leading CG sequences on Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire (2005). He later moved to Prime Focus, where he became CG Supervisor on films such as Mirror Mirror (2012) and Poltergeist (2015), before returning to Framestore.

At Framestore, he played a key role in the Marvel Cinematic Universe, working as CG Supervisor on Guardians of the Galaxy Vol. 2 (2017), Avengers: Infinity War (2018) and Avengers: Endgame (2019). His early pre-production work on Avengers: Endgame was especially notable for helping to develop the machine-learning system used to bring the “Smart Hulk” character to life. He was promoted to VFX Supervisor at Framestore for Doctor Dolittle (2020), The Little Mermaid (2023), Wonka (2023), Deadpool & Wolverine (2024), and The Fantastic Four: First Steps (2025).

For Avengers: Endgame (2019), he was nominated for a Visual Effects Society Award for Outstanding Animated Character in a Photoreal Feature for “Smart Hulk”, and for Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire (2005), he was nominated for Outstanding Created Environment in a Live Action Motion Picture for the Black Lake environment.', dob = null, photo_url = null
    WHERE id = 2887;
UPDATE [dbo].[people]
    SET biography = N'Terel Gibson, ACE, is an American film and television editor. Gibson has held primary editing roles on several high-profile feature films, including the satirical dark comedy Sorry to Bother You (2018), the thriller Ready or Not (2019), the poignant biographical drama The Last Full Measure (2020), and the comedy-drama Mr. Roosevelt (2017), among others. His feature credits also include The Road Within (2014), We Are Your Friends (2015), The Ballad of Lefty Brown (2017), Girlfriend’s Day (2017), and All Nighter (2017).

Born and based in Los Angeles, Gibson is a graduate of Emory University and built his filmmaking foundation through roles as assistant editor on films like Spanglish (2004), Little Miss Sunshine (2006), Pride and Glory (2008) and Orphan (2009), under the guidance of lead editors such as Pamela Martin and Lisa Zeno Churgin. He often credits his mentors, including Lisa Churgin and Pam Martin, for shaping both his creative approach and professional ethos.

In television, Gibson has worked on notable television series, including Marvel Studios’ Hawkeye (2021), where he served as editor on episodes “Never Meet Your Heroes” and “Hide and Seek”. He has also edited projects like Safety and Think Like a Dog (2020).

In a February 2021 profile for the Motion Picture Editors Guild’s “Cut to Black” series, Gibson reflected on early cinematic influences such as Alfred Hitchcock’s Rear Window and the PBS documentary Eyes on the Prize, which helped ignite his passion for storytelling and editing. He expressed a steadfast belief that “it’s not just how you start, it’s how you finish,” a tenet he attributes to Lisa Churgin and carries with him through each project. Remembering his earliest on-camera appearance, he recounted a small acting moment in Jonathan Demme’s Beloved before realising that his true calling lay behind the editing suite.', dob = null, photo_url = 'https://image.tmdb.org/t/p/w500/ytrVgfS3iJgPUGkSCSCUMcG88nR.jpg'
    WHERE id = 2888;
