UPDATE [dbo].[people]
    SET biography = N'Holly Dowell is a stunt performer affiliated with the Screen Actors Guild‐American Federation of Television and Radio Artists (SAG-AFTRA), based in Atlanta and Chicago. She has been recognized for her work with nominations for the SAG Awards Stunt Ensemble category for her contributions to "Guardians of the Galaxy Vol. 3" (2024) and "Loki" Season 1 (2021).

Dowellnulls filmography includes stunt performances in major productions such as "Black Panther: Wakanda Forever" (2022), where she was credited as a stunt performer, and "Thor: Love and Thunder" (2022), where she served as a stunt double. In addition to her stunt work, she has appeared on-screen in roles like a Fight Club Member in "Chick Fight" (2020) and as a Blonde Actress in "Jackpot!" (2024).

On television, Dowellnulls credits encompass a range of series. She performed stunts in "Hawkeye" (2021), serving as an additional stunt double for Hailee Steinfeld across five episodes. Her other TV work includes stunt performances in "Loki" (2021), "Cobra Kai" (2021), "Dynasty" (2021), "Black Lightning" (2021), "Utopia" (2020), "Stargirl" (2020), "Chicago Fire" (2019), "Chicago P.D." (2019), and "Instinct" (2019).

Dowellnulls skill set is extensive, encompassing fighting techniques suitable for film, including kickboxing and jujitsu. She is trained in performing full-body and partial fire burns, high falls up to 25 feet, wire work, stair falls, and mini-trampoline stunts. Her special skills also include ice skating, ice hockey, powerlifting, and track and field, and she holds a private pilot license.

Her contributions to the stunt industry are further highlighted by her involvement with LBP Stunts Chicago, where she has been part of the stunt and fight teams for various film and television projects.', dob = null, photo_url = 'https://image.tmdb.org/t/p/w500/6A6zWKA9Kd918zytyXIfwbk8fJU.jpg'
    WHERE id = 6815;
UPDATE [dbo].[people]
    SET biography = N'Aja was born in Seattle, Washington. Her athletic ability was evident from a young age. By elementary school she was racing and beating all the boys on the playground. Born to Soun Frary, a ballerina dancer and her father, Lee Leavy, California State High School Wrestling Champion; Ajanulls athletic genes set the stage for her future. Aja excelled as a 3 sport high school athlete and by college earned a full scholarship as a Track and Field Heptathlete at San Diego State University.

Aja went onto become a Division 1 NCAA Bronze Medalist and earned All-American Honors by her senior year. In 2000, while still a collegiate athlete, Aja was one of the youngest competitors at the Olympic Trials, placing 9th. After college Aja was accepted into the United States Olympic Training Center program where she was able to train full time and compete across the country and the world. In 2004 an injury struck just before her most promising Olympic Trails competition. While healing, a college friend knew she would make an ideal stunt double and stunt performer. Her first movie was on a film called American Gangster in 2006. Her career took off after her first film and since then has become one of the countries most sought after Stuntwoman.

In 2016 she became a member of the Stuntwomenulls Association of Motion Picture, one of Ajanulls highest career highlights.', dob = '1978-07-01', photo_url = 'https://image.tmdb.org/t/p/w500/CnFD5UlbVt0w5TN3HpkT2FROpa.jpg'
