UPDATE [dbo].[people]
    SET biography = N'Berkely Mather the pseudonym of John Evan Weston-Davies, was a British author who published fifteen novels and a book of short stories. He also wrote for radio, television and the movies.

Genghis Khan (1965) is a novelisation of the 1965 film of the same name, for which he had written the original story. Mathernulls other motion picture credits include The Long Ships and Dr. No with Mather borrowing a copy of Flemingnulls original novel from his son. Mather also provided uncredited rewrites of the screenplays for From Russia with Love and Goldfinger.

James Bond film producers Albert R. Broccoli and Harry Saltzman purchased the film rights to The Pass Beyond Kashmir for Columbia Pictures in 1963. Sean Connery and Honor Blackman were to star. Production was to have begun in late 1964 in Britain and on location in the Far East.', dob = '1909-02-25', photo_url = 'https://image.tmdb.org/t/p/w500/zH2VClgYRGwIDuAcbkQUZ1F89Bb.jpg'
    WHERE id = 8034;
UPDATE [dbo].[people]
    SET biography = N'Ted Moore, BSC (7 August 1914 – 1987) was a South African-British cinematographer known for his work on seven of the James Bond films in the 1960s and early 1970s. He won the Academy Award for Best Cinematography for his work on Fred Zinnemannulls A Man for All Seasons, and two BAFTA Awards for Best Cinematography for A Man for All Seasons and From Russia with Love.', dob = '1914-08-07', photo_url = 'https://image.tmdb.org/t/p/w500/7tIDoGQh7EaHdPfU0CRAVupuMlC.jpg'
    WHERE id = 8035;
UPDATE [dbo].[people]
    SET biography = N'Peter Roger Hunt (11 March 1925 – 14 August 2002) was a British director, editor and producer of film and television, best known for his work on the James Bond film series, first as an editor and then as a second unit director. He finally served as director for On Her Majestynulls Secret Service. His work on the series helped pioneer an innovative, fast-cutting editing style.', dob = '1925-03-11', photo_url = 'https://image.tmdb.org/t/p/w500/e4vWC9qvG7xGghvuqHcPnO1o8wx.jpg'
    WHERE id = 8036;
UPDATE [dbo].[people]
    SET biography = N'The name is "Maibaum, Richard Maibaum".....the brilliant screenwriter who adapted the Ian Fleming 007 novels into the highly entertaining screenplays of nearly every James Bond film from Dr. No (1962) through to Licence to Kill (1989).

Maibaum attended New York University, then studied acting at the University of Iowa. By the time he was in his late twenties, Maibaum was a well established Broadway actor and playwright. He entered films as a screenwriter in 1937, spending the war years with the armynulls Combat Film Division. In 1946, he joined Paramount as both screenwriter and producer, contributing to such films as The Big Clock (1948) and The Great Gatsby (1949).

From advice that making films abroad was an excellent tax shelter, Maibaum formed a partnership in the 1950s with producers Irving Allen and Albert R. Broccoli This led to his involvement in the phenomenally successful James Bond series of the 1960s and 1970s and, after Ian Fleming, Maibaum has arguably been the person most responsible for shaping the image of the screenulls most famous spy!', dob = '1909-05-26', photo_url = 'https://image.tmdb.org/t/p/w500/sqjcu780KEimvNeCaliaVLmth64.jpg'
